---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout title="Miles to Kilometers for Runners: 5K, 10K, Marathon" description="Convert common running distances between miles and kilometers. Includes 5K, 10K, half marathon, and marathon distances with pace conversion tips." keywords="miles to kilometers running, 5K in miles, 10K in miles, marathon distance, running pace conversion, km to miles runner, race distance">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Length</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">Miles to Kilometers for Runners: 5K, 10K, Marathon</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 12, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>Running events are named in kilometers (5K, 10K) but many runners think in miles. Whether you are training on a treadmill set to miles or racing a metric event, here is the complete guide to distance conversions for runners.</p>

      <h2>The Conversion</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">1 mile = 1.60934 km | 1 km = 0.62137 miles</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Common Race Distances</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>5K</strong> = 3.107 miles (most popular entry-level race)</li>
        <li><strong>10K</strong> = 6.214 miles</li>
        <li><strong>15K</strong> = 9.321 miles</li>
        <li><strong>Half Marathon</strong> = 21.0975 km = 13.109 miles</li>
        <li><strong>Marathon</strong> = 42.195 km = 26.219 miles</li>
        <li><strong>Ultra Marathon (50K)</strong> = 31.07 miles</li>
        <li><strong>Ultra Marathon (100K)</strong> = 62.14 miles</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Pace Conversion: min/km vs min/mile</h2>
      <p>Pace is where it gets tricky. Here are common running paces in both units:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>4:00 min/km = 6:26 min/mile (elite runner)</li>
        <li>5:00 min/km = 8:03 min/mile (strong amateur)</li>
        <li>5:30 min/km = 8:51 min/mile (good recreational)</li>
        <li>6:00 min/km = 9:39 min/mile (steady jogger)</li>
        <li>7:00 min/km = 11:16 min/mile (easy pace)</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Quick formula:</strong> To convert min/km to min/mile, multiply by 1.609. To go the other way, multiply min/mile by 0.621.</p>

      <h2>Using the "8 and 5" Rule</h2>
      <p>For quick mental estimates while running, remember that 8 km is roughly 5 miles. This gives you a handy multiplier:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>5 miles done = about 8 km done</li>
        <li>10 miles done = about 16 km done</li>
        <li>If your goal is 10K, you need to run about 6.2 miles</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Treadmill Tips</h2>
      <p>Most treadmills in the US display speed in miles per hour. To match a km-based training plan:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>To run at 5:00 min/km, set the treadmill to 7.5 mph (12 km/h)</li>
        <li>To run at 6:00 min/km, set it to 6.2 mph (10 km/h)</li>
        <li>To run at 4:30 min/km, set it to 8.3 mph (13.3 km/h)</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Whichever unit you prefer, the distance is the same. The finish line does not care if you counted in miles or kilometres.</p>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/length" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Length Converter →</a>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/convert/length" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Converter →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
